KW  - climate-smart agriculture
KW  - Tobit model
KW  - CONSERVATION AGRICULTURE
KW  - SMALLHOLDER FARMERS
KW  - ADAPTATION
AB  - Agriculture is the pillar of Ethiopia's economy and livelihood and the most important driver of employment creation, export earnings, and poverty reduction. However, smallholder perceptions in lowland, semiarid zones of study areas like Konso were under-researched and sociopsychological or institutional barriers on climate-smart agricultural practices (CSAPs) were inadequately explored. This study delved into factors that influence the adoption and farmers' perception toward CSAPs. The research used mixed and systematic sampling techniques. A total of 182 samples of household heads were taken from Wozeqa, Holte, and Fuchucha kebeles of Arba Minch Zuria, Derashe, and Karat Zuria woredas, respectively, in the South Region. Data were analyzed using descriptive and inferential statistics of right-censored Tobit model. The right-censored Tobit model shows that among the explanatory variables, namely, sex, age, and availability of mulching materials significantly affected the intensity of adoption for CSAPs (p < 0.01). Moreover, the use of credit and attending trainings significantly affected the adoption of CSAPs (p < 0.05) and having information on the adoption of selected CSAPs (p < 0.01). In the study areas, the majority (60%) of respondents implemented agroforestry, whereas 18% of respondents cultivate improved crop varieties. 64% of respondents agreed that the use of climate-resilient crop varieties increased the yield of crops like sorghum, and 72% of respondents said that conservation agriculture increased the yield of crops. Socioeconomic, demographic factors, and lack of stakeholders' communication were the main determining factors that influenced respondents' adoption of CSAPs. Providing training for farmers on CSAPs, the development agents' commitment was also suggested to enhance farmers' adoption of CSAPs in the study areas.
