KW  - economic resilience
KW  - resilience
KW  - resilience index
AB  - Economics resilience refers to the capacity of households, individuals, communities, nations, and systems to effectively cope with, adjust to, and bounce back from different shocks and pressures. Since there is heightened susceptibility to climate variability, market volatility, and sociopolitical upheavals, smallholder farmers in the Asayita district encounter ongoing difficulties in maintaining their livelihoods and achieving economic stability. This study investigates the economic resilience through crop-livestock Integration (CLI) among small-holder farmers in the Asayita district. The study employed stratified and simple random selection techniques with multistage sampling to select 360 households from four kebeles. The data were analyzed using the beta regression model and the economic resilience index (ERI). In the research area, the average degree of ERI among rural households was 0.38, with the lowest and maximum values being 0.01 and 0.79, respectively. The beta regression model showed that while distance from cannel had a negative effect on the degree of ERI, the sex of the household head, educational status, CLI participation, tropical livestock unit, nonfarm job, and access to information all had statistically significant and positive effects. The study's conclusions suggest measures that household heads, district and regional authorities, as well as national and international organizations, should do to improve the district's economic resilience.
