AB  - Research on the gendered impacts of conservation agriculture (CA) on farmers' labour dynamics in Asia is limited, and very little of that work employs a feminist analysis. This study applies the concept of social reproduction to examine how CA reorganises agricultural and reproductive labour and its gendered implications. A mixed methods approach with a cross-sectional survey, micro-focus group discussions (FGDs) and key informant interviews in Terai, Nepal, is applied. It reveals the introduction of CA to have increased farmers' workloads and reorganised agricultural labour at the individual level but without greatly restructuring gendered agrarian labour both in production and reproduction. While women have experienced a sense of empowerment and social acceptance as productive members of agrarian communities, this has had limited impact on any renegotiation and redistribution of reproductive labour. Furthermore, engagement in CA activities has created a transitional space where newly constructed subjectivities of 'productive women', coexist, contest and undergo negotiation with the traditional subjectivities of 'reproductive women', leading to rapid transformations in gender dynamics. In this space, women's social reproduction continues to subsidise agricultural and rural development while compromising their own labour reproduction, putting them at risk of depletion. We argue that agricultural innovation if not rigorously evaluated for its gendered consequences, may exacerbate the labour burdens of subsistence women farmers and further deepen the feminisation of the social reproduction crisis in Nepal and elsewhere.
