FX  - This work was supported through a grant from the University of Oslo. We are grateful to Jans Bobert and Khamaldin Mutabazi in the project Resilient Agro-landscapes to Climate Change in Tanzania for invaluable support and advice during the fieldwork. We acknowledge Sokoine University of Agriculture for granting the research permit and we are grateful for the key information and advice we obtained from academic staff at the University. Many thanks are also due to the excellent group of MSc students who worked as enumerators during the fieldwork. We thank Matthew P. Kent and Mariann Arnyasi at the Centre for Integrative Genetics (CIGENE), Department of Animal and Aquacultural Sciences, Norwegian University of Life Sciences, Aas, Norway for the genotyping services. This study would not have been possible without the information provided by the late Dr. Alfred Moshi, the breeder of the most used improved OPVs in the study area. In agreement with the Agricultural Research Centre in Ilonga, Moshi supported this study by providing breeder's seeds. We are also grateful to Kevin Pixley at CIMMYT for providing information about the breeding populations used in the breeding of the two OPVs investigated in this study. Insightful comments from two anonymous reviewers improved the final version.
