TI  - Assessing Social, Economic and Environmental Challenges of Veld Fires in South Africa: A Case Study of Capricorn District Municipality in Limpopo Province
T2  - JOURNAL OF SUSTAINABLE FORESTRY
LA  - English
KW  - Veld fires
KW  - community
KW  - vulnerability
KW  - community resilience
KW  - South Africa
KW  - food security
KW  - CLIMATE-CHANGE
AB  - The frequency and severity at which veld fires occur in the Capricorn District Municipality of Limpopo Province and South Africa have seen a sharp increase in the past three decades. These happenings are directly linked to global warming and climate change, human negligence, changing farming techniques and population growth. The occurrences of these fires have exposed human life and properties to very high risk, loss of huge tracts of farmlands, habitats and biodiversity, accelerated unemployment and significant threat to sustainable livelihoods among the population. Using a triangulated research approach, this paper explored the root causes of veld fires in the country and weaknesses within the current policies and programmes designed to address the problems of veld fires in the country and particularly in the Capricorn District Municipality in the Limpopo Province. This paper, therefore, recommends an urgent need to strengthen existing collaborations among key stakeholders, namely, the government, farmers' associations, communities, and traditional leaders, including private organizations such as insurance companies and other financial entities. The paper further suggests incorporation of sustainable indicators and building resilience through a holistic framework for mitigating risks, and complex systems science for forest management and forest capacity to withstand the impacts of climate change.
