AB  - This study is aimed at to identify factors affecting the smallholder farmers' asset accumulation in threshold parameters as welfare indicators in lowland areas of south Ethiopia. The cross-sectional data were obtained from 384 smallholder mung bean producer farmers in the lowlands of Wolaita, Gamo, and Gofa zones using a multistage sampling technique. The data was analyzed by ordered probit model and multiple correspondence analysis was used to develop the composite asset index from 38 asset indicators based on suitability assessment. Results indicated that, the difference in asset accumulation ranges to 4.78, which explains the wide unequal distribution over the study area. The threshold parameters of <= 0.394 for very poor, 0.394 <= y(i)(& lowast;) <= 1.043 for poor, 1.043 <= y(i)(& lowast;) <= 1.611 for medium, 1.611 <= y(i)(& lowast; )<= 2.28 for rich, and >= 2.28 for very rich asset cut points indicated that they are significantly different from each other so the five ordered status should not be combined into one. In addition, the asset accumulation of mung bean farmers was high likely and significantly influenced by family size, quantity of mung bean produced in a year, road distance from home, the count of climate adaptation strategies and livelihood strategies such as mixed farming and off-farming, with the base category of crop production. Farmers' home distance from farm plots and from farmers training centers were less likely to affect asset accumulation status. Factors such as road distance, farm distance, distance from the farmers training center, diversification of livelihoods, and uptake of the adoption strategy should be seriously considered by policy makers, government bodies, stakeholders and research institutes to encourage farmers to adopt stress-tolerant varieties. Moreover, they should also improve transportation logistics to ease access to the center market. Therefore, these findings provide significant policy implications regarding smoothing elongated shocks, strengthening resilience, and stabilizing the livelihood of the smallholder mung bean farmers through increasing the asset accumulation.
