AB  - This study on jackfruit farming provides important insights into present waste management techniques, awareness and perception of climate change, and potential adoption of a circular economy in Eastern Visayas. Jackfruit farmers were predominantly older adults with a mean age of 55, female, and majority were married. Respondents rely on non-farming income, making jackfruit farming their supplementary livelihood. While farmers have a great desire to adopt sustainable practices, obstacles such as insufficient tools, technology, and technical support impede growth. Climate change awareness has a favourable impact on waste management decisions, yet most existing practices remain linear, with minimal engagement in circular economy engagement. A notable practice is a successful initiative in Leyte island involving black soldier fly (BSF) and frass fertilizer production. This project demonstrates the efficient conversion of organic waste into high-value products larvae and highlighting both the economic viability of BSF systems and their alignment with circular economy principles by reducing waste and generating valuable agricultural inputs. To encourage a circular economy practice in jackfruit farming, some feasible recommendations include focusing on expanding access to technology, training, disseminating information and establishing supporting infrastructure. Inputs.
