AB  - The impacts of anthropogenic climate change may be felt through changes in modes of natural climatic variability. The El Nino-Southern Oscillation (ENSO) is the most important year-to-year fluctuation of the climate system, varying between anomalously cold (La Nina) and warm (El Nino) conditions. Underpinning occurrences of ENSO events is the positive feedback between trade wind intensity and zonal contrasts in sea surface temperature (SST), referred to as the Bjerknes feedback. The trade winds normally pile up warm surface water in the western Pacific while upwelling colder subsulface water in the east along the equator and off the west coast of South America. The resulting east-west surface temperature contrast reinforces an east-west air pressure difference across the basin that in turn drives the trade winds. During La Nina, the system strengthens; but during El Nino, the trade winds weaken as atmospheric pressure rises in the western Pacifi & eogon; and falls in the eastern Pacific. The Bjerknes feedback now operates in reverse, with weakened trade winds and SST warning tendencies along the Equator reinforcing one another. These swings in temperature are accompanied by changes in the structure of the subsurface ocean, the position of atmospheric convection and associated global teleconnection patterns. ENSO is spawned in the tropical Pacific, but its reach is global. It alters the general circulation of the atmosphere from one season to the next through far-field teleconnections, leading to droughts, floods, heat waves, and other extreme weather events across our planet. These natural hazards have widespread impacts on human and natural systems, including agriculture, public health, power generation and consumption, financial markets, transportation, tourism, freshwater resources, civil conflict, wildfires, fisheries, marine and terrestrial ecosystems, and biodiversity. The character of ENSO depends on the long-term average background climatic conditions on which it develops. However, because of human activities since the start of the Industrial Revolution in the mid-18th century, these background conditions have been changing at a pace that has greatly accelerated in recent decades. We have come to appreciate just how profound these changes are, thanks to five Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change assessments since 1990.<br /> In this review, we provide an update from the community since 2021, on the progress of changing ENSO and its impacts under greenhouse warming. Latest climate models suggest that a warming pattern featuring faster warming in the eastern Pacific than in the surrounding regions is possible as greenhouse warming progressively overwhelm other factors including decadal climate variability; that ENSO variability post-1960s has already increased from that pre-1960 characterized by an increase in strong El Nino, strong La Nina, and multiyear La Nina events, consistent with the projected increase pre-100; and that the long-term change in ENSO SST variability is likely to be detected by 2030 in the eastern equatorial Pacific. Further, the changing mean state and increase in ENSO variability have intensified two-way interactions between the tropical and extratropical North Pacific, increased variability of the Western Pacific Subtropical High, increased SST variability over the north tropical Atlantic, hastened warming over the Antarctic shelf ocean, and exacerbated the economic cost of global warming.
   Under persistent greenhouse warming into 2300, the increased ENSO pre-2100 reverses, to a subsequent reduction as the faster warming in the equatorial eastern Pacific develops into a permanent El Ning-like condition, highlighting a strong nonlinear ENSO response.
