AB  - Agricultural food production in China is deeply vulnerable to extreme droughts. Although there are many studies to evaluate this issue from different aspects, comprehensive assessments with full consideration of climate change, crop rotations, irrigation effects, and socioeconomic factors in broad scales have not been well addressed. Considering both the probability of drought occurrence and the consequential yield losses, here we propose an integrated approach for assessing past and future agricultural drought risks that relies on multimodel ensemble simulations calibrated for rice, maize, and wheat (RMW) in China. Our results show that irrigation has reduced drought-related yield losses by 31 +/- 2%; the largest reductions in food production were primarily attributable to socioeconomic factors rather than droughts during 1955-2014. Unsustainable water management, especially groundwater management, could potentially cause disastrous consequences in both food production and water supply in extreme events. Our simulations project a rise of 2.5 similar to 3.3% in average rice, maize, and wheat productivity before 2050 but decrease thereafter if climate warming continues. The frequency of extreme agricultural droughts in China is projected to increase under all examined Representative Concentration Pathway (RCP). A current 100-year drought is projected to occur once every 30 years under RCP 2.6, once every 13 years under RCP 4.5, and once every 5 years under RCP 8.5. This increased occurrence of severe droughts would double the rate of drought-induced yield losses in the largest warming scenario. Policies for future food security should prioritize sustainable intensification and conservation of groundwater, as well as geographically balanced water resource and food production.
AD  - Tsinghua Univ, Dept Earth Syst Sci, Minist Educ, Key Lab Earth Syst Modeling, Beijing, Peoples R ChinaAD  - Univ Oxford, Environm Change Inst, Oxford, EnglandAD  - UVSQ, CNRS, CEA, Lab Sci Climatet Environm, Gif Sur Yvette, FranceAD  - Leibniz Inst Agr Dev Transit Econ IAMO, Halle, Saale, GermanyC3  - Tsinghua UniversityC3  - University of OxfordC3  - Universite Paris SaclayC3  - CEAC3  - Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique (CNRS)C3  - Leibniz AssociationC3  - Leibniz Institut fur Agrarentwicklung in Transformationsokonomien (IAMO)FU  - Ministry of Science and Technology of the People's Republic of China (MOST) grant [2017YFA0603602]; National Natural Science Foundation of China grant [41371491]
FX  - We thank Peng Gong, Guangwen Yang, Xiaomeng Huang, Haohuan Fu, Wei Xue, and Xinghua Han for their support in this research. The Sunway Taihu Light Supercomputer was tremendously helpful in completing the computational tasks. This research was supported by the Ministry of Science and Technology of the People's Republic of China (MOST) grant 2017YFA0603602 and National Natural Science Foundation of China grant 41371491. The data sources include the following. Historical data of crop yields, food production, planting costs, market prices, per capita consumption, fertilizer use, planting area, and irrigation area at the provincial and national levels since the 2000s are compiled from statistical yearbooks published by National Bureau of Statistics of China (NBS of China, 2000-2015, http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjsj/ndsj). The provincial and national data before the 2000s are from the book of "China Compendium of Statistics 1949-2008" (NBS of China, 2010). The source of the county-level data is from the Department of Crop Production in the Ministry of Agriculture (http://www.zzys.moa.gov.cn/). Soil properties are derived from "soil database of China for land surface modeling" (Shangguan et al., 2014, http://globalchange.bnu.edu.cn/research/soil2). Water resource and usage information are based on records compiled from Ministry of Water Resources (1997-2015, http://www.mwr.gov.cn/zwzc/hygb). Historical weather (temperature and precipitation) data are provided by China Meteorological Administration (http://cdc.nmic.cn). Surface radiation fluxes are from Sheffield et al. (2006). Surface air relative humidity and wind speed are from Zhang et al. (2014). Land use data are from Gong et al. (2013). Crop distribution maps are from Ramankutty et al. (2008). GCM output for future climate scenarios under IPCC CMIP5 is acquired from the archive maintained by the Program for Climate Model Diagnosis and Intercomparison at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (https://pcmdi.llnl.gov/search/cmip5/). The climate models include BNU-ESM (from Beijing Normal University); CNRM-CM5 (from Centre National de Recherches Meteorologiques at Meteo France); GFDL-CM3, GFDL-ESM2G, and GFDL-ESM2M (from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory); IPSL-CM5A-MR (from the Institute Pierre Simon Laplace); and MIROC5, MIROC-ESM, and MIROC-ESM-CHEM (from the Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology, the University of Tokyo, and the National Institute for Environmental Studies). Three future climate change scenarios (Representative Concentration Pathways) are considered: RCP 2.6, RCP 4.5, and RCP 8.5. The three crop models are run independently using the individual model outputs from each of these climate change scenarios. To assess future trends in agricultural yields, GCM-based RMW yields for 2006-2014 based on each GCM and RCP scenario are normalized to match average 2006-2014 yields from the historical baseline irrigation or rainfed scenarios.
