AB  - Climate-induced risks in Himachal Pradesh significantly disrupt crop production and impact the livelihoods of farmers. Agricultural insurance is crucial for managing these uncertainties and mitigating potential financial losses. This study explored two key questions: What amount are farmers willing to pay for the Pradhan Mantri Fasal Bima Yojana? And, what are the factors influencing their decision to purchase such insurance policies? A mixed-method sampling approach was used to survey 300 farmers across five districts. The Double-Bounded Dichotomous Choice (DBDC) method was employed to estimate farmers' average willingness to pay (WTP), while the Tobit regression model was used to analyze the factors that significantly influence their willingness to purchase crop insurance. Results showed mean WTP per hectare for maize (Rs. 610), paddy (Rs. 638), and wheat (Rs. 526), exceeded the actual premium rates of Rs. 600, Rs. 400, and Rs. 600, respectively. Factors such as access to extension services, literacy, farm income and ease of enrollment significantly influenced WTP. The study recommended raising awareness, ensuring timely claim settlements and improving credit access can enhance scheme uptake. These steps can strengthen risk management, promote economic stability and increase the resilience of farming communities.
