AB  - This study examines whether reducing structural constraints to gender equality in agrifood systems, specifically those related to norms and access to resources, contributes to women's empowerment in agriculture, more gender-equal climate adaptive capacities and better dietary outcomes for women. We test these hypotheses by examining the effects of a first intervention called ECATTO, which addressed discriminatory norms and attitudes related to gender-based violence and supported women's rights and leadership, and a second intervention, SHOUHARDO III, which addressed gender-unequal access to resources and extension services for agriculture and livestock; both were implemented in the Kishoreganj district, a climate hotspot in Bangladesh. We rely on gender-disaggregated intrahousehold data collected between treatment and control populations in March 2023 and use propensity score matching as a quasi-experimental identification method. Our study findings confirm that challenging structural barriers to gender equality associated with discriminatory gender norms and attitudes and enhancing gender-equal access to resources and extension services support women's empowerment in climate-affected agrifood systems. Enhancing gender-equal access to resources and extension supports more gender-equal adoption of climate-smart agricultural and livestock practices, suggesting a promising avenue to simultaneously improve gender equality and climate-adaptive capacity. Challenging discriminatory norms and attitudes improved women's diet diversity.
