AB  - The depletion of inshore fishery resources and growing demand for aquatic products have accelerated the expansion of offshore mariculture. Nevertheless, climate change, combined with the industry's reliance on static management approaches, constrains its sustainable development and climate resilience. This study aims to develop a spatiotemporal decision-making framework of offshore mariculture based on Dynamic Energy Budget (DEB) models. The goal is to identify the optimal stocking and harvesting times for overwintering tiger puffer (Takifugu rubripes) at various stocking sizes (50, 100, 150, and 200 g) in South China under both current and future climate scenarios (SSP1-2.6 and SSP5-8.5). Additionally, the study evaluates the spatiotemporal suitability of these conditions by analyzing the specific growth rates during the grow-out phase to generate spatial suitability maps. Our results indicate that optimizing the stocking date can reduce the production cycle by up to 76 days, and larger-sized fingerlings (150g and 200g) display shorter culture periods and wider suitable farming windows. Climate projections further indicate that suitability patterns differ markedly between low-emission (SSP1-2.6) and high-emission (SSP5-8.5) scenarios, with future warming leading to a contraction of optimal farming windows. Overall, this study provides a novel, dynamic framework that integrates daily-scale temporal optimization with spatial suitability assessment. It advances precision mariculture by moving beyond static planning and offers a practical tool for climate-adaptive management in offshore mariculture. Future studies can incorporate additional environmental stressors and socioeconomic constraints to enhance the framework's applicability to management decisions of offshore mariculture.
