AB  - Agricultural sustainability in Indigenous and smallholder systems faces increasing challenges from the expansion of input-intensive agriculture and changing socio-environmental conditions. While the importance of social networks and Indigenous knowledge for sustaining agroecological practices is widely recognized, limited empirical research has examined how specific network interactions are associated with the adoption of sustainable practices in the Global South. This study adapts and extends the Agricultural Knowledge Systems (AKS) framework to incorporate both knowledge and resource flows within farmers' egocentric networks. Drawing on survey data from 220 Aymara smallholders in northern Chile, the analysis combines a participatory environmental sustainability index, multilevel egocentric network mapping, and econometric modeling. Results show that the type of central actors within farmers' networks-particularly peers, organizations, or input suppliers-are associated with differing sustainability outcomes. Peer advice and organizational participation show positive associations with sustainability, while centrality of input suppliers and reliance on wholesale markets are linked to lower sustainability scores. Additionally, gender and full-time agricultural dedication each independently are associated with sustainable practice adoption; women are generally more likely to adopt such practices, though this advantage diminishes when they farm full time. No significant association was found for technical advice and government support for sustainability, suggesting a need to reconsider the alignment of policy incentives and advisory services with socio-environmental goals. These results highlight the importance of fostering peer-based exchanges and facing women's structural barriers to advance sustainability in Indigenous agricultural systems. The study also provides evidence of the value of egocentric network analysis for analyzing farmers decisions related to sustainability in marginalized farming communities.
